cantile lineages, which were further bolstered by the gender regime and the local religious order. As Guo demonstrates, the discrepancy between representation and practice helps explain Huizhou's triumphs. The more active the economy became, the more those central to its commercialization embraced conservative sociocultural norms. Home lineages embraced neo-Confucian orthodoxy even as they provided the financial and logistical support to assure the success of Huizhou merchants. The end result was not ";capitalism"; but a gentrified mercantile lineage culture with Chinese-or Huizhou-characteristics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aKinshipzChinazShe Xian (Anhui Sheng)xHistory. 0aMercantile systemzChinazShe Xian (Anhui Sheng)xHistory. 0aMerchantszChinazShe Xian (Anhui Sheng)xHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520385221zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520385221zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520385221/original  a978-3-11-076649-3 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA